<subSubSection id="738F518DFFC73E1EFF01FF55FC396433" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3B2A0206FFC73E1EFF01FF55FC396433" blockId="93.[151,1437,152,323]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis id="09E1DE14FFC73E1EFF01FF55FE8265C3" bold="true" box="[199,335,152,179]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Discussion:</emphasis>
This species is known from a single female specimen, collected on Mt. Moffat in Carnarvon National park, 
<collectingRegion id="F951CCE4FFC73E1EFEE7FF70FE6465A7" box="[289,425,189,215]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">Queensland</collectingRegion>
. Although no male has been collected, a fragment of the DNA barcode was successfully obtained from the 
<typeStatus id="E42EBCA4FFC73E1EFEA4FF2CFE0A658B" box="[354,455,225,251]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">holotype</typeStatus>
, so if a male is collected in the future it can be confidently matched to the 
<typeStatus id="E42EBCA4FFC73E1EFB3EFF2CFA97658B" box="[1272,1370,225,251]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">holotype</typeStatus>
using DNA evidence. The barcode data extracted from the 
<typeStatus id="E42EBCA4FFC73E1EFD2DFEC8FC80646F" box="[747,845,261,287]" pageId="93" pageNumber="94">holotype</typeStatus>
is publicly available on the BOLD website (Process ID: SYRAU381-18), as detailed above in the Materials and methods section.
</paragraph>
